{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504047"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:09:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:09:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2292"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2292"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.44,0.4,0.01,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111875"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2292"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93947"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1009"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4839"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11683"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"558"},{"type":"contributions","id":"576"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1265"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7209"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14254"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43120"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111875"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old man with moderate dementia was disruptive in the nursing home facility where he resides. He has displayed aggressive behaviours such as verbally abusing other nursing home residents and throwing his utensils on the ground during mealtimes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn one incident, he sat in the dining room without touching his food on the table. He started moving the dining chairs and tables around and started throwing utensils on the floor when he was ordered to stop his disruptive behaviour. As a result, the locum GP was called to separate him from the rest of the nursing home residents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has also been rude and verbally aggressive towards nursing staff, particularly when they attempt to change his wet adult diapers. His recent MMSE is 15/30.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What is the most appropriate first management strategy to try to reduce his disruptive behaviour?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cognitive behaviour therapy","Diversion therapy","Prescribe him with low-dose risperidone","Ignore his behaviour and allow him to vent his aggression","Reminiscence therapy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiversion therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be a useful and simple first-line strategy to engage him in activities that he is interested in. The aim is to divert older adults\u2019 attention to activities that calm them, these therapies must be person-centered and can be passive or active. Examples with proven benefits to reduce agitation include guided imagery, singing, progressive muscle relaxation or even dancing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECognitive based therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate because he has poor cognition due to his dementia \u2013 this is also the incorrect behaviour therapy for dementia patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgnoring his behaviour \u003C/strong\u003Ewill not address or change his behavioural issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-psychotic medication, such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eprescribing low dose Risperidone, \u003C/strong\u003Eshould only be prescribed for behavioural and psychological symptoms if there is danger to others or themselves as antipsychotic use for dementia is only marginally effective and is associated with side effects of cognitive decline, increased risk of stroke and earlier mortality. Therefore, this is not the right management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReminiscence therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is a treatment that uses the five senses to help dementia patients remember events and people. This therapy could be a form of distraction but is often used as a second option.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diversion therapy should be the first-line management approach for patients with dementia and verbally abusive behaviour.","Anti-psychotic medication should only be prescribed for behavioural and psychological symptoms if there is danger to others or themselves"],"references":["Kirkham J, Sherman C, Velkers C, Maxwell C, Gill S, Rochon P et al. Antipsychotic Use in Dementia. The Canadian Journal of Psychiatry. 2016;62(3):170-181.","Dementia Australia. Therapies and communication approaches [Internet]. Dementia.org.au. 2020. Available from: https://www.dementia.org.au/national/support-and-services/carers/therapies-and-communication-approaches","Fitzsimmons, S., Barba, B., \u0026 Stump, M. (2015). Diversional and physical nonpharmacological interventions for behavioral and psychological symptoms of dementia. Journal of Gerontological Nursing, 41(2), 8-17."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93947"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2292"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93947"},"attribu